p96
sg36
Nsg37
VLast night, my mother listened to an opinion that she did not share. She found an add in a magazine stating "Not all autistics want to be cured". I have been telling her this for years, but she never listened to me until she saw it on her own.<br /><br />I was very happy. I then took this as an opportunity to show her some parts of the autism community she had refused to see before. First, I showed her a video I found at Autreat called 'No Pity'. Then I showed her part of the presentation that the same person made on <a href="http://vimeo.com/12901883">grading autistic people</a>.<br /><br />Why did I show her videos first? In the past, I have given her links but she never looked. Usually she said something about me slanting the stuff I gave her to support my side of the argument and refused to look. I sat down and watched these videos with her. She had to look. I wanted to open her mind a bit with the videos to get her thinking about the issues.<br /><br />Afterwards, I gave her a few links to various websites. We had a discussion that nearly degenerated into an argument but we stopped it before it did. That was great. It was the best conversation I have had with her in a long time.<br /><br />Today she printed some pages from the links I gave her. She does that when she really wants to read something. It took close to sixteen years, but she is open-minded about autism now. She does not agree with me on most issues still. However, she is thinking about my views and she listened to me. That is enough.<div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width="1" height="1" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/1848101302710400415-2400189845463846137?l=shadowmechanic.blogspot.com" alt="" /></div>
