S'text/html'
p144
sg36
Nsg37
VThe internet was the first place I passed as male. Initially I did not know why, but it made me happy whenever someone referred to me as he. The internet also aided in my discovery of the term transgender and, in a way, validated my feelings about it. It made me realise that it was not just me and it was not just a quirk related to autism.<br /><br />Fast forward several years. I changed my name on the school email. One of my mom's friends read her son's email and saw this. Despite it being a gender neutral name, she told my mom and my mom panicked. This was before I was out to her.<br /><br />Several months later I sent in a proposal for a presentation at an autism conference. A couple months after it was accepted. I corresponded with some people attending the conference. By then I had changed my name on my email to my male name. I sent the proposal in my birth name. The person running the conference contacted me about it because ze was confused. Ze was amazingly understanding and kept my name one way on the site while changing my name tag for the conference. I presented under my male name.<br /><br />However, using multiple names is confusing. Sometimes I try to stick to my gender-neutral screen name but I am switching that back. This becomes horribly confusing when talking to people at the lab. Some people at the lab know about this and others do not. A new person started helping my PI and she thought that she was talking to two different people.<br /><br />What is my solution? Against what people say I should do, I am going to have to be completely out and consistent at the lab. Proposals for conferences and the like will still be under my birth name for a bit. However, I will put the name that I want on my first scientific paper. That is my right.<div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width="1" height="1" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/1848101302710400415-7060505654680321248?l=shadowmechanic.blogspot.com" alt="" /></div>
