S'text/html'
p188
sg36
Nsg37
VI recently checked the DSM V for updates on their proposed changes to the criteria for autism. I was pleasantly surprised. It seems to be nearing completion. Before reading further, please click <a href="http://www.dsm5.org/ProposedRevisions/Pages/proposedrevision.aspx?rid=94">here</a> and read all four tabs.<br /><br />What they did makes sense. After all, social interaction and communication should fall in the same domain. Merging these also is a step forward in removing the stigma around autistics who cannot speak. The general set of criteria also begins to crack ideas about autistics being a certain, particular way.<br /><br />I find the page on severity particularly interesting. I have never supported functioning levels when used to describe autistics or the differentiation between autism, asperger's, and PDD (which are the same disorder). That said, the severity page is tasteful. It works for insurance purposes and will help more people get the coverage they need. It also does not pick out any particular skills as being the determining factor in support or degrade people who have certain deficits. It simply speaks in terms of support required. I hope that documents like this become more prevalent and help in breaking down the barriers that people face. This is probably the best outcome at this time. I hope that the DSM committee does not drastically modify their proposed criteria before publication.<div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width="1" height="1" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/1848101302710400415-6389469492698624578?l=shadowmechanic.blogspot.com" alt="" /></div>
