S'text/html'
p274
sg36
Nsg37
VToday I joined the school chorus. I sang for four years in middle school but I have not since. Back then, I did not know how to read music and mostly picked things up by ear. I still do. This is changing.<br /><br />In the past several months, I started to care about music a whole lot more. I really loved singing in middle school so joining a chorus was the natural place to start. Actually, for me, research is the first place. When I get interested in something, I want to be good at it. I searched a bit and found a conservatory music program for high schoolers. My mom and I contacted a few teachers there. I also found a chorus that sings medieval music but it meets too late at night. I hope to join this later.<br /><br />I did go to that chorus that meets late at night once. It was great. Everyone accepted me as a guy with no questions. I even successfully sang tenor (my voice is quite low). Afterwards, I showed one of my friends the music and he pointed me to the school chorus, saying that I should show the teacher this music because he loves early music.<br /><br />I went and talked to the teacher who runs the chorus that day. I showed him the music and told him about my plans to start lessons at the conservatory. He seemed very interested in it. Then he asked if the chorus that I had been to that one time was a mixed or all male group. I was surprised. He thought I was a guy. This made me very happy.<br /><br />However, there was also a slight issue. The parts when singing are gendered and, as faculty in a small school, he was going to find out that I am biologically female one time or another. Until then, I had just sung tenor or jumped between alto and baritone (in middle school when we did not have a tenor section). Joining this chorus was my first semi-serious step into the world of music. I wanted to train my voice like a male would because after I go on testosterone my voice will drop. Also, I dislike being lumped with the girls and the higher notes in the alto range are very hard for me to reach.<br /><br />I talked to the faculty member who runs the GSA. I am no longer allowed to go to the GSA but I still talk to the teacher in charge of it. He offered to talk to the chorus teacher for me. I guess he did too.<br /><br />Today I just walked in and he handed me some music. He said that my voice might be a tenor or countertenor but he would try me as a tenor today. It went well. Everyone else already knew the music a bit and had more musical experience so I was a bit quiet. But the person teaching referred to me as a guy. And no one stopped him. I want to keep it this way if I can.<br /><br />I have no idea what will happen at the conservatory or if my parents will find out about school and get angry. However, even when you are afraid, you have to do what will make you happy. Otherwise there is no point in doing it at all.<div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width="1" height="1" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/1848101302710400415-4119774413413105291?l=shadowmechanic.blogspot.com" alt="" /></div>
