VMost people do not remember much of their childhood. Even those memories retained are unreliable. I remember a lot, at least those things of interest to me. The rest I do not remember at all. This is how my memory seems to work and it is not uncommon to find this sort of memory among autistics.<br /><br />I remember fleeting thoughts about gender but for the most part I just thought that these were another part of me being different from the other kids. Here are some of my memories.<br /><br />In preschool, I would spend time with the older boys out making forts. I loved this and they accepted me as one of their own.<br /><br />At age four, I asked my mom how babies were made and how the parents chose the gender. As I was young and my mom was very religious, she told me that the parents prayed to God very hard for a child. In these prayers, they specified the gender. I then asked about changing gender. She said that if a person prayed very hard then God may change his or her gender. My mom denies she ever said this.<br /><br />Around age four I started rejecting skirts, dresses, and most types of tights. This was partially because of sensory issues that made them uncomfortable but also because they felt wrong as a whole.<br /><br />At age five, I would walk around the playground playing a game with a friend where we pretended to be characters from the show Dragon Tales. I was always the male dragon.<br /><br />My hobbies were never particularly feminine or masculine. I played outside, read books, used the computer, and was interested in everything to do with animals. I had both dolls and trucks but I never really played much with either. When I played with toys, they were either sensory things like play-doh or animal figures which would be pawns in my epic stories.<br /><br />In elementary school, I lead playground wars. I did not get in trouble for this until fourth grade, surprisingly. I always played with younger kids because they were easier to interact with and they never bullied me. In the winter, we would go sledding down a small hill and build snow forts. I did not have good friends but people tolerated me even if most stayed away from me and thought of me as a freak.<br /><br />I was never good at sports. This is both fortunate and unfortunate. If I was, I might have told my parents earlier but life would have been more unbearable. I would also have to deal with what others thought. At the school I was at, the only academically-inclined kids seemed to be girls. I still spent time with boys though when I played. For the most part I was a social outcast but I did interact with others a bit. I quickly learned to not care what others thought about me.<br /><br />However, some moments still shine through where I thought about gender. I always loved dressing like my dad on father's day and dreaded mother's day. Eventually I fought to wear pants to church and for school photos. I still looked like a girl but at least I was not in a dress or a skirt.<br /><br />In first grade, one girl mentioned that her father called her a tomboy. I asked what that meant. She said a girl who acts like a boy. I liked this word. It was the closest thing I had to describing myself.<br /><br />In the school plays, I always was happy with the unisex costumes that we wore. It was one area where there was no gender separation in clothing or anything.<br /><br />In third grade, the clothes I wore under one Halloween costume looked very masculine. I liked this. It made me happy, although I did not know why. Until then, I just liked bright clothes with animals on them.<br /><br />When sledding, I always liked the snowpants and clothes the boys had on. I eventually got some that looked a bit more like it. In general I ignored clothes. That was the first I really thought about them.<br /><br />I spent most of my time all through middle school in my own imaginary world. There I was just me. I could be a boy in my own world. Almost all of the other characters in my world were male as well.<br /><br />When I started going online, I identified myself as female in habit. However, when someone said he when talking about me, I felt a surge of joy. I eventually left gender on forums blank and let people guess. Most of the time they guessed male. In roleplay games I would always play a male character as well.&nbsp; <br /><br />These are only a few of my memories on my prepubescent thoughts on gender. For the most part, I ignored it. I grew up in a conservative town in Maine but gender roles were not too strictly enforced. As a child, the only things different between the other boys and me were clothing and hairstyle. I could live with this as I never care for looks or how others perceive me. My childhood was not easy; I was lonely, strange, and dealing with other issues. However, the real trials were not apparent yet.<div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width="1" height="1" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/1848101302710400415-4506805249939568360?l=shadowmechanic.blogspot.com" alt="" /></div>
