Vp { margin-bottom: 0.08in; }  <br /><div>Disclaimer: Events might not be reported exactly as they occurred. People mentioned hold no responsibility for their roles in this. For all anyone knows, I could be making this up. </div><div><br /></div><div>I write from the darkest days of my short life. Dark, yet somehow shining towards the future at once. A future so bright that it makes the darkness itself shine. Indeed, sometimes I stop in my tracks blinded by the light. I have come to tolerate, even enjoy, the shadows. This is the forbidden story I have penned about my journey.</div><div><br /></div><div> The real storm began on a bright, June day in Massachusetts. June twenty-fourth. I woke up late as usual. Teenagers do that. The second summer semester had not yet started and that day was a day off from the lab. I had already finished my presentation for the conference so there was no harm in staying home. Staying home would not be relaxing though and I knew it. I had known it for three months.</div><div><br /></div><div> At around noon J. arrived in her beaten up six-year-old car, bought just one year after she started working with me. She entered the house quickly and began her meeting with my mom to learn of the days tasks. She was a no-nonsense kind of woman like that. Most of the time.</div><div><br /></div><div> My mother surely gave her all sorts of unreasonable requests to get me to do insane numbers of chores under the guise of 'independent living'. Okay, so I did have to learn some of the things like picking up after myself, doing laundry, taking care of my dog, and even some minor cooking. I did all of them for J. Not my mom though. I always stayed away from her.</div><div><br /></div><div> About a half an hour after J. arrived she ventured upstairs. In near silence we began the day's chores. We both knew what today was; June 24<sup>th</sup>, the day that would change everything. In the end we walked down to the Koi pond as my white, fluffy dog trotted along next to us.&nbsp;</div><div><br /></div><div> \u201cI am nervous. How will my mom react?\u201d I finally asked.</div><div><br /></div><div> \u201cI have no idea but you have prepared for it as best as you can. I still do not think you should tell her now. Telling her when you are in college would be much easier,\u201d J. wisely replied.</div><div><br /></div><div> I disregarded it, \u201cHow will she react? You are good at reading people. Surely you must have some idea.\u201d</div><div><br /></div><div> We stood overlooking the Koi pond staring at the orange fish darting amongst the lilly pads, hardly visible. I chastised my dog for trying to take a drink. J. stood and though.</div><div><br /></div><div> Finally she responded. \u201cWell, I think she will cry a lot and it will take her a while to go through the stages of grief. She is a religious woman and this changes her whole idea of the child she was raising. She will still love you though.\u201d</div><div><br /></div><div> At this point we turned and slowly walked up the hill, dreading to reach the house where our conversation must end.</div><div><br /></div><div> \u201cAt least we are going away right after this. Then she can have some time to herself to think this over,\u201d I said.</div><div><br /></div><div> \u201cYes, that will probably be for the best.\u201d</div><div><br /></div><div> We looked on as my dog dashed after a squirrel and circled the tree as if she expected it to come down and play with her. Then she dove onto the grass head-first and rolled. We sat down underneath a large tree and let her flail and tumble on the ground.</div><div><br /></div><div> \u201cWhat do you think of this whole situation?\u201d I asked. I already knew the answer but I needed someone to reassure me that I was not crazy.</div><div><br /></div><div> \u201cYou know what I think. I will always love and accept you no matter who or what you are; man, woman, or person. Even if you decided you were a dog I would accept it.\u201d</div><div><br /></div><div> I stifled a laugh. It was a reference to my days spent as a programmer for a furry roleplay game. We both looked off into the distance as the wind blew through the grass and trees.</div><div><br /></div><div>J. finally spoke up. "This seems like the beginning of a coming of age story. It is just like the ones I have read."</div><div><br /></div><div>"Yes, the calm before the storm as well." I agreed.</div><div><br /></div><div>Looking back, it was. It was even like a certain book I read in middle school about a Massachusetts boy in a summer session at a school before everything went downhill. The beginning might be the only thing in common with that story. It became a modern conflict quite quickly.</div><div></div><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img width="1" height="1" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/1848101302710400415-7498654610560878721?l=shadowmechanic.blogspot.com" alt="" /></div>
